This solution uses a breadth-first search (BFS) approach to find the minimum number of swaps required to transform `s1` into `s2`. BFS is suitable for this problem because it explores all possible states level by level, ensuring that the first time we reach `s2`, it is with the minimum number of swaps. The `get_neighbors` function generates all possible strings that can be formed by swapping one pair of characters in the current string, starting from the first position where the current string and `s2` differ. This ensures that we are only making swaps that can potentially lead to `s2`.
